4) External Validation of eMFD¶

In this notebook, we examine the performance of the eMFD when scoring news documents. Specifically, we contrast moral signal extracted by the eMFD with signal extracted by the original MFD (MFD; Graham, Haidt, & Nosek, 2009) and MFD2.0 (Frimer et al., 2017). For this validation study, a separate, hold-out set of 1,985 news articles will be used that was not part of the eMFD annotation task. To extract the moral information contained in these news articles, we rely on eMFDscore (https://anonymous.4open.science/r/de12c047-d322-4686-95a2-3391e377a4a8/ ). eMFDscore is a Python library that we have developed for the fast and flexible extraction of moral information from textual input documents. Specifically, we executed the following three commands to obtain moral information extracted from each dictionary:

  • $emfdscore data/validation_article.csv emfd bow emfd_output.csv

  • $emfdscore data/validation_article.csv mfd bow mfd_output.csv

  • $emfdscore data/validation_article.csv mfd2 bow mfd2_output.csv

For the Moral Entity Framining analysis, the following command was executed:

  • $emfdscore data/validation_article.csv emfd pat pat_output.csv

def boxplot(df, img_name, label, title):
    g = sns.boxplot(x="variable", y="value",
            data=df)
    sns.despine(offset=20, trim=False)
    sns.swarmplot(x="variable", y="value", data=df,
              size=1, color=".7", linewidth=0, alpha=0.5)
    g.set_xticklabels([x.split('_')[0].capitalize() for x in df.variable.unique()], rotation=35)
    g.set_ylabel(label)
    g.set_xlabel('')
    g.set_ylim(bottom=0,top=0.2)
    g.set_title(title)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig('plots/'+img_name, dpi=300)
    return

2) Correlations between Word Scores Across Dictionaries¶

To semantically triangulate the eMFD word scores, we first correlated the word scores computed by the eMFD with word scores computed by the MFD and MFD2.0. We find that the strongest correlations appear between equal moral foundations across dictionaries.

from scipy.stats import pearsonr

def calculate_pvalues(df):
    df = df.dropna()._get_numeric_data()
    dfcols = pd.DataFrame(columns=df.columns)
    pvalues = dfcols.transpose().join(dfcols, how='outer')
    for r in df.columns:
        for c in df.columns:
            pvalues[r][c] = round(pearsonr(df[r], df[c])[1], 5)
    return pvalues

3) Partisan News Framing¶

Previous studies have shown that conservatives tend to place greater emphasis on the binding moral foundations including loyalty, authority, and sanctity, whereas liberals are more likely to endorse the individualizing moral foundations of care and fairness (Graham et al., 2009). To test whether the eMFD can capture such differences within news coverage, we contrasted the computed eMFD word scores across Breitbart (conservative leaning), The New York Times (centrist), and The Huffingtonpost (liberal leaning)

4) Correlations with GDELT Topics¶

Next, we examined how the obtained word scores of the eMFD correlate with the presence of various topics in each news article. To obtain topics that are being discussed in each article, we rely on news article metadata provided by GDELT (Leetaru & Schrodt, 2013). GDELT’s theme (i.e., topic) dictionaries draw on an extensive list of keywords and subject-verb-object constellations to extract news topics of, for example, climate change, terrorism, social movements, protests, and many others. For the purpose of this analysis, we focus on 16 morally-relevant topics (see SM Section 8.3 for topic descriptions). These include, among others, discussions of armed conflict, terror, rebellions, and protests

5) Prediction of News Article Engagement¶

As a next validation step we tested how accurately extracted moral information by the eMFD predicts social media share counts of news articles compared to previous MFDs. We chose the context of news engagement for validation purposes as previous studies suggest a link between moral cues in news articles and tweets, and sharing behavior (Brady et al., 2017; Valenzuela et al., 2017). To obtain the number of times a given news article in the validation set was shared on social media, we utilized the Application Programming Interface (API) of sharedcount.com, which queries share counts of news article URLs directly from Facebook.

6) Moral Entity Framing¶

The majority of moral acts – regardless of their valence (i.e., whether they connote evil or good) – are typically linked to at least two different entities: An entity engaging in the moral or immoral act (a moral agent), and another to be target of the moral or immoral behavior (a moral target; Gray & Wegner, 2009). In this final validation analysis, we demonstrate the capability of eMFDscore to extract the moral actions in which entities engage in as well as the moral actions that befall them. By relying on syntactic dependency parsing (SDP), eMFDscore first extracts the dependencies among words in a sentence, for instance, to determine subject-verb-object constellations. Second, by combining SDP with named entity recognition (NER), eMFDscore extracts the moral words for which an entity was declared either to be the agent/actor or the patient/target. For example, in the sentence: The United States condemned North Korea for further missile tests, the United States is the agent for the word condemned, whereas North Korea is the target for the word condemned. Furthermore, rather than extracting all words that link to agent-patient dyads, only moral words are retrieved that are part of the eMFD.

trump_agent_word = pd.DataFrame(trump_agent, columns=['word']).set_index('word')
trump_agent_word = trump_agent_word.join(emfd).sort_values('care_p', ascending=False).drop_duplicates()
trump_agent_word['counts'] = pd.Series(Counter(trump_agent))
trump_agent_word['moral_sum'] = trump_agent_word[probabilities].sum(axis=1)
trump_agent_word['moral_score'] = trump_agent_word['counts'] * trump_agent_word['moral_sum']
trump_agent_word = trump_agent_word.iloc[pd.np.where(trump_agent_word[probabilities].ge(0.15).any(1, skipna=True))]
trump_agent_dict = trump_agent_word.sort_values('moral_score', ascending=False).head(20)[['moral_score','counts']].T.to_dict()
trump_agent_words = trump_agent_dict.keys()
